    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/39acb52ff074bc477f0325f4b1960c90?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 95910,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 260990,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/260990/jigar-joshi",
                "reputation": 241442,
                "display_name": "Jigar Joshi",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 333,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1412951360,
            "creation_date": 1300264071,
            "body": "<p>Suppose you have  <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>boolean active;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Accessors method would be<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public boolean isActive(){return this.active;}\n\npublic void setActive(boolean active){this.active = active;}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>See Also<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Java_Programming/Java_Beans\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Java Programming/Java Beans<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/codeconvtoc-136057.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Code Conventions for the Java Programming Language<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n",
            "answer_id": 5322666,
            "question_id": 5322648,
            "last_edit_date": 1412951360
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0fb744889b28b6c24a058e9d721c20d4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 29965,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 81367,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/81367/narayan",
                "reputation": 6311,
                "display_name": "Narayan",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 126,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1547042197,
            "creation_date": 1300284480,
            "body": "<p><a href=\"http://geosoft.no/development/javastyle.html#Specific\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://geosoft.no/development/javastyle.html#Specific<\/a><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <ol start=\"14\">\n  <li><p><em><code>is<\/code><\/em> prefix should be used for boolean variables and methods.  <\/p>\n  \n  <p><code>isSet<\/code>, <code>isVisible<\/code>, <code>isFinished<\/code>, <code>isFound<\/code>, <code>isOpen<\/code><\/p><\/li>\n  <\/ol>\n  \n  <p>This is the naming convention for\n  boolean methods and variables used by\n  <strong>Sun for the Java core packages.<\/strong>  Using the is prefix solves a common\n  problem of choosing bad boolean names\n  like status or flag. isStatus or\n  isFlag simply doesn't fit, and the\n  programmer is forced to chose more\n  meaningful names. <\/p>\n  \n  <p>Setter methods for boolean variables\n  must have set prefix as in: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>void setFound(boolean isFound);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n  \n  <p>There are a few alternatives to the is\n  prefix that fits better in some\n  situations. These are has, can and\n  should prefixes: <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>boolean hasLicense(); \nboolean canEvaluate(); \nboolean shouldAbort = false;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 5326487,
            "question_id": 5322648,
            "last_edit_date": 1547042197
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/aLKQa.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 138128,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 342852,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/342852/sean-patrick-floyd",
                "reputation": 300632,
                "display_name": "Sean Patrick Floyd",
                "accept_rate": 97
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 89,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1300264527,
            "creation_date": 1300264527,
            "body": "<p>For a field named <code>isCurrent<\/code>, the correct getter / setter naming is <code>setCurrent()<\/code> / <code>isCurrent()<\/code> (at least that's what Eclipse thinks), which is highly confusing and can be traced back to the main problem:<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Your field should not be called <code>isCurrent<\/code> in the first place.<\/strong> <em>Is<\/em> is a verb and verbs are inappropriate to represent an Object's state. Use an adjective instead, and suddenly your getter / setter names will make more sense:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>private boolean current;\n\npublic boolean isCurrent(){\n    return current;\n}\n\npublic void setCurrent(final boolean current){\n    this.current = current;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 5322730,
            "question_id": 5322648
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bb5230985aa2c9ea7d022d1a16890f16?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 32277,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 89391,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/89391/miku",
                "reputation": 189354,
                "display_name": "miku",
                "accept_rate": 79
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 9,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1719240214,
            "creation_date": 1300264170,
            "body": "<p>According to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaBean\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">the JavaBeans article on Wikipedia<\/a> it would be:<\/p>\n<pre><code>void setCurrent(boolean current)\nboolean isCurrent()\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 5322685,
            "question_id": 5322648,
            "last_edit_date": 1719240214
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/p5lgA.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 15974771,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 11527968,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/11527968/jimmy",
                "reputation": 1071,
                "display_name": "Jimmy"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 7,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1678428378,
            "creation_date": 1633156110,
            "body": "<p>There is a markable point between <em><strong>setter/getter<\/strong><\/em> method of the data type <strong>Boolean<\/strong> and <strong>boolean<\/strong> in side a class ( for <em>pojo/entity<\/em>).<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>For both Boolean and boolean the <em>setter<\/em> method should be <em><strong>setXXX()<\/strong><\/em> but <em>getter<\/em> method would be <em><strong>getXXX()<\/strong><\/em> and <em><strong>isXXX()<\/strong><\/em> respectively<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p><strong>Example:<\/strong><\/p>\n<p><strong>(a)<\/strong> if property is defines as <strong>Boolean<\/strong><\/p>\n<pre><code>private Boolean check;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>the setter/getter method<\/p>\n<pre><code>public Boolean getCheck() {   // getXXX()\n    return check;\n}\n\npublic void setCheck(Boolean check) {\n    this.check = check;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p><strong>(b)<\/strong> if property is defines as <strong>boolean<\/strong><\/p>\n<pre><code>private boolean check;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>the setter/getter method<\/p>\n<pre><code>   public boolean isCheck() {   // isXXX()\n        return check;\n    }\n    public void setCheck(boolean check) {\n        this.check = check;\n    }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 69414543,
            "question_id": 5322648,
            "last_edit_date": 1678428378
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d831264327d63f3c1994bca5104b2302?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1665095,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1532672,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1532672/christian-vermeulen",
                "reputation": 576,
                "display_name": "Christian Vermeulen"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1478603801,
            "creation_date": 1478603801,
            "body": "<p>Maybe it is time to start revising this answer? Personally I would vote for <code>setActive()<\/code> and <code>unsetActive()<\/code> (alternatives can be <code>setUnActive()<\/code>, <code>notActive()<\/code>, <code>disable()<\/code>, etc. depending on context) since \"setActive\" implies you activate it at all times, which you don't. It's kind of counter intuitive to say \"setActive\" but actually remove the active state.<\/p>\n\n<p>Another problem is, you can can not listen to specifically a SetActive event in a CQRS way, you would need to listen to a 'setActiveEvent' and determine inside that listener wether is was actually set active or not. Or of course determine which event to call when calling <code>setActive()<\/code> but that then goes against the Separation of Concerns principle.<\/p>\n\n<p>A good read on this is the FlagArgument article by Martin Fowler: <a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/bliki/FlagArgument.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://martinfowler.com/bliki/FlagArgument.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>However, I come from a PHP background and see this trend being adopted more and more. Not sure how much this lives with Java development.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 40485512,
            "question_id": 5322648
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b5faa5f92233942cebf571b4b84322d5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 4935971,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3974072,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3974072/tim-t",
                "reputation": 303,
                "display_name": "Tim T"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1607925291,
            "creation_date": 1607925291,
            "body": "<p>It should just be get{varname} like every other getter.  Changing it to &quot;is&quot; doesn't stop bad variable names, it just makes another unnecessary rule.<\/p>\n<p>Consider program generated code, or reflection derivations.<\/p>\n<p>It's a non-useful convention that should be dropped at the first available opportunity.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 65284245,
            "question_id": 5322648
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6562b04efea7bad8bb846bbc6f5cf5a1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 24238330,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 18191094,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/18191094/henry-s",
                "reputation": 588,
                "display_name": "Henry S."
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1654895901,
            "creation_date": 1654895901,
            "body": "<p>It is highly recommended to use an <strong>adjective<\/strong> to name a boolean field. If you generate getter and setter using IntelliJ, you will find out that the getter is <code>isCurrent()<\/code> for both of boolean fields <code>current<\/code> and <code>isCurrent<\/code>.<\/p>\n<p>We can take a look at <a href=\"https://github.com/JetBrains/intellij-community/blob/master/plugins/lombok/testData/after/getter/GetterBoolean.java\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">IntelliJ community source code<\/a>, its test data shows that no matter whether your boolean field name starts with <code>is<\/code> or not, the name of getter starts with <code>is<\/code>.<\/p>\n<pre><code>class Getter {\n  boolean foo;\n  boolean isBar;\n  boolean hasBaz;\n\n  @java.lang.SuppressWarnings(&quot;all&quot;)\n  public boolean isFoo() {\n      return this.foo;\n  }\n\n  @java.lang.SuppressWarnings(&quot;all&quot;)\n  public boolean isBar() {\n      return this.isBar;\n  }\n\n  @java.lang.SuppressWarnings(&quot;all&quot;)\n  public boolean isHasBaz() {\n      return this.hasBaz;\n  }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n<p>It will be very confusing when you want to call the getter, when you boolean field name starts with <code>is<\/code>. Besides, when your colleagues want to get the value of a boolean field you defined, they will only know the getter' s name instead of the field' s name. In that case, the prefix <code>is<\/code> is not necessary.<\/p>\n<p>Here is another example, when I retrieve data from database to instantiate a object of Employee, the value of <code>isRetired<\/code> is always <code>false<\/code>. Because Java does not find an appropriate setter, the value of a boolean field is always default value, say <code>false<\/code>, which is not expected.<\/p>\n<pre><code>class Employee{\n    private int age;\n    private boolean isRetired;\n\n    ...\n    public boolean setRetired(boolean isRetired){\n        this.isRetired = isRetired;\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 72579935,
            "question_id": 5322648
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a49819ba92ac7353f2d8ba0fd965f15?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 12853278,
                "user_type": "unregistered",
                "user_id": 9297401,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9297401/mkne",
                "reputation": 1,
                "display_name": "Mkne"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1517447597,
            "creation_date": 1517447597,
            "body": "<pre><code>private boolean current;\n\npublic void setCurrent(boolean current){\n    this.current=current;\n}\n\npublic boolean hasCurrent(){\n    return this.current;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 48553914,
            "question_id": 5322648
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef8bd3e0c603a5fc8fa9600885b32bb4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 41228,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 119772,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/119772/suraj-chandran",
                "reputation": 24897,
                "display_name": "Suraj Chandran",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -5,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1378922648,
            "creation_date": 1300264135,
            "body": "<pre><code>Setter: public void setCurrent(boolean val)\nGetter: public boolean getCurrent()\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>For booleans you can also use <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public boolean isCurrent()\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 5322678,
            "question_id": 5322648,
            "last_edit_date": 1378922648
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f423f167e87b35215a5fece70acf3d54?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 14164369,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 10232700,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10232700/amekusa",
                "reputation": 1,
                "display_name": "amekusa"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": -6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1534407338,
            "creation_date": 1534407338,
            "body": "<p>As a setter, how about:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>// setter\npublic void beCurrent(boolean X) {\n    this.isCurrent = X;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>or<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>// setter\npublic void makeCurrent(boolean X) {\n    this.isCurrent = X;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I'm not sure if these naming make sense to native English speakers.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 51872523,
            "question_id": 5322648
        }
    ],
